And though in his estimate ol these causes, my author dwells almost too exclusively on ecclesiastical abuses, it will not be difficult sor us to see that those abuses were at once an effect and a cause, and that the greediness‚ selfishness, neglect oi duty, and political perfidy which cha· racterised the churchmen ol the fisteenth century were possible in the clergy by reason that they were even more rise and more scandalous in the laity.

The war which Henry commenced was carried on vigorously by John, Duke of Bedlord, who was two years younger than the king. There was only a year’s interval between each of the three younger sons, Thomas, Duke oi Clarence, having been born in 1388, and Humphrey oi Gloucester‚ the youngest of the four, in 1389. Thomas had been killed at Beauge in 1421. The administration of home affairs was generally in the hands ol the younger brother, whose impetuous temper and rash acts embroiled him with his uncle, the Bishop of Winchester. These differences began as early as 1424, and lasted with little intermission till

grave scandals in the Roman Court (p.154), and might have caused serious complications between England and the Papacy (p. 17) had , not the Pope’s death occurred.

But a curse seemed to hang over the House ol Lancaster. The three sons ol Henry the Fourth married and were childless, two ol them, the Dukes ol Bedsord and Gloucester‚ having married twice. In 1446 it seemed that the family would become naturally extinct, unless issue might be expected from the King and Queen who had been married in the summer of 1445.
